Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

  • Mediteranean cuisine has the highest cost of order, while Japanese has the lowest cost of order.
  • Vietnamese and Korean have the lowest median cost of orders, yet they have the lowest number of orders as previously noticed
  • Korean cuisine has some outliers on both the higher and lower cost of orders side, while Mediterranean and Vietnamese have outliers on the higher cost of orders side.
  • Half of the cuisine types have a median cost of orders below 16 dollars, while the other half have a median cost of orders above 16 dollars.
  • The French cuisine has the highest median cost of order above 20 dollars.

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [50]:
# The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants.
# The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4.
# Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer.

# Used to take care of the error: A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a DataFrame
pd.options.mode.copy_on_write = True

# Create a new data set with only valid ratings. 'Not given' is an invalid rating
data_valid_ratings = data[data['rating'] != 'Not given']

# Change the data type of the ratings column to a numeric type to be able to find the mean
data_valid_ratings['rating'] = data_valid_ratings['rating'].astype(float)

# Create the final data set with the given criteria (rating count over 50 and average rating over 4)
data_ratings_final = data_valid_ratings.groupby('restaurant_name').agg({'rating': ['mean', 'count']}).sort_values(by=('rating', 'count'), ascending=False)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [51]:
# Create a copy of the data
data_charges = data.copy()

# Initialize net revenue
net_revenue = 0

# Loop through the 'cost_of_the_order' column to generate the net revenue of the company
for charge in data_charges['cost_of_the_order']:
  if charge > 20:
    net_revenue += charge * 0.25
  elif charge > 5:
    net_revenue += charge * 0.15
  else:
    net_revenue += 0

# Output the net revenue
print(f"Net Revenue generated by the Company: ${net_revenue:.2f}")

# Other ways to do this
# Loop through the data to create a new column with the company's charge for each order
for index, row in data_charges.iterrows():
    if row['cost_of_the_order'] > 20:
        data_charges.loc[index, 'charge'] = row['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25
    elif row['cost_of_the_order'] > 5:
        data_charges.loc[index, 'charge'] = row['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15
    else:
        data_charges.loc[index, 'charge'] = 0

revenue = data_charges['charge'].sum()
print(f"Net Revenue generated by the Company: ${revenue:.2f}")

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [52]:
# What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed?
# (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.)

# Create a copy of the data
data_total_delivery_time = data.copy()

# Calculate the total delivery time and store it in a column
data_total_delivery_time['total_delivery_time'] = data_total_delivery_time['food_preparation_time'] + data_total_delivery_time['delivery_time']

# Calculate the number of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered
orders_more_than_60 = data_total_delivery_time[data_total_delivery_time['total_delivery_time'] > 60].shape[0]

# Calculate the percentage of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered
orders_more_than_60_perc =orders_more_than_60 / data_total_delivery_time.shape[0] * 100

print('The number of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed is:', orders_more_than_60)
print('The percentage of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed is:', round(orders_more_than_60_perc, 2), '%')

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The cost of the orders ranges from around 4.50 dollars to 35.50 dollars, while the average cost of the orders is around 16.50 dollars.
  • Half of the cost of the orders are less than 14.50 dollars, which is below the average value, which indicates that most of the orders are not very costly.
  • The time to prepare the food ranges from 20 to 35 minutes. The mean and median are both ~27 minutes.
  • The time to deliver the food ranges from 15 to 33 minutes. The mean and median of the time to deliver the food are ~24 and 25 minutes respectively.
  • The most popular cuisine is American with close to 600 total orders followed by Japanese, Italian and Chinese with about 475, 300 and 200 total orders, respectively.
  • Vietnamese is the least popular cuisine with just below 10 total orders
  • The number of orders during the weekends is more than double that of the weekdays with about 1350 orders during the weekends and about 550 orders during the weekdays
  • Quite a number of orders, above 700, were not rated - 'Not given'. Of the rated orders, close to 600 were rated a 5, close to 400 were rated a 4, and close to 200 orders were rated a 3.
  • The number of orders rated a 5, were approximately double the rest of the ratings.
  • Almost half of the customers paid less than 14 dollars for their order and 50% of the cost of the order amounts lie between 12 to 22.5 dollars.
  • There is some level of symmetry between the food preparation times.
  • About half of the orders were prepared in less than 27 minutes and 50% of the orders were prepared in between 23 to 31 minutes.
  • About half of the orders were delivered in less than 25 minutes and 50% of the orders were delivered in between 20 to 28 minutes.
  • The top 5 restaurants in terms of orders received are Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, Parm with 219, 132, 119, 96 and 68 order, respectively
  • The most popular cuisine on weekends is American with 415 orders, followed by Japanese with 335, Italian with 207 and Chinese with 163 orders, respectively
  • 29.24% of the orders cost more than 20 dollar
  • The average order delivery time is 24.16 minutes
  • The ID and number of orders of the top 3 customers are 52832 with 13 orders, 47440 with 10 orders, and 83287 with 9 orders
  • The American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese cuisines are the most popular and have the lowest cost of orders. Perhaps, that is why they have the most orders due to their prices being generally lower. Also, their median are some of the lower ones.
  • Mediteranean cuisine has the highest cost of order, while Japanese has the lowest cost of order.
  • Vietnamese and Korean have the lowest median cost of orders, yet they have the lowest number of orders
  • Half of the cuisine types have a median cost of orders below 16 dollars and the French cuisine has the highest median cost of order above 20 dollars.
  • The min and max food preparation times are similar for most of the cuisine types
  • The Vietnamese and Korean cuisines have the lowest median food preparation times of about 25 minutes
  • The food preparation median times for the American, Indian, Chinese, Mediterranean and Middle Eastern cuisines are similar at about 27 minutes
  • All cuisine types have more orders on weekends than on weekdays
  • A majority of the cuisine types have majority of unrated orders
  • A majority of the cuisine types have a rating of 5 as their highest rating amongst the rated values and then 4s
  • The Thai and Spanish cuisines have ratings of 4s and 5s, with no 3s
  • The mean and median of the delivery time for the week days is about 28 minutes, while that of the weekend is about 22 minutes
  • It takes longer to delivery the food during the week days than during the weekend, as the min, median and max delivery time during the week days are considerably higher than those of the weekend
  • There is really no deducible relationship between the rating and delivery time
  • The longer the average food preparation times, the lower the rating and the shorter the food preparation times, the higher the rating
  • The average food preparation times is inversely corelated to the ratings
  • Interestingly, the cost of the order is directly corelated to the rating; meaning that as the mean cost of the order goes up, the rating goes up. Very interesting!
  • There is no visible relationship between the cost of the order and the food preparation time
  • There is no meaningful corelationship between any of the numerical pairs

Recommendations:¶

  • FoodHub should look for ways to get more orders rated for even better data analysis. For example, incentives, like special discounts, could be given to customers if they rate their order
  • FoodHub should look for ways to increase weekday orders. For example, incentives, like special or higher discounts, could be given to customers if they order during the week
  • Partnerships with more restaurants that serve American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese cuisines should be pursued, since these are the most popular, and generate the most revenue.
  • For customers ordering the most popular cuisines - American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese, discount coupons can be offered for either current or future orders being placed towards purchase of the less popular cuisines like Vietnamese, Korean and Spanish in the bid to incentivise the customers to order those cuisines also.
  • The analyses show that the more popular cuisines - American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese actually generally have lower cost of orders. So, it only goes to say that the customers ordering these cuisines will most likely continue to order them because of their lower prices. To attempt to lure customers to order the other types of cuisines, incentivising customers to place these orders like with discounts or lowering their prices, might be a good option
  • In general, offering discounts across the board has the potential to increase revenue and also enhance customer satisfaction, thereby increasing ratings; so, that could be a way to go to drive business, enhance customer experience and increase revenue
